Capt. Hector's Log book. November 14th, 1887:

I set foot upon the place where everything frozen still, where our presence have disturbed the everlasting emptiness of Void's Approach. My hands tucked into the coat, conserving the what little warmth my body has.

"We're going to need a few hours to fix the ship, captain" Maybe's Daughter spoke. "Unless you want this beauty sink into the Zee, never to be found again" The Tireless Mechanic added. I agreed to give them all the time they need to fix the ship, after all, we're not in a hurry.

To keep myself from going mad I decided to gather intelligence, if there's anything to gather here at all. This stillness was itself of interest to the Admiralty. It's not impossible someone foolish might attempt to open the gate. It's not inconceivable that it might open from the other side. And what then?

Some time passed, and yet the work is still not done. So I decided to look at the stars for a while to pass the time. These were real stars. They burnt above the roof of the Neath, beyond the earth, in the spaces of heaven. Even so far away, even now, their eyes are on me - but here in the night under the world, I am safe - safe -

I returned to my senses, gasping. My hands were cold, numb. How long have I been watching the stars?

"Captain" A crewman called out, I scrambled from the sandy shores (was I lying on the ground?) and looked at them. "There's a rumor of something, buried in the icy depths by the gate's edge. We want to prove the rumors, would you like to go with us?" I nodded and asked them to lead the way before following behind, their chattering turned into a background noise. Still reeling from what happened moments ago.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
